image.latex-image:
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.62, >=stealth]
    \draw[->] (-4.7,0) -- (4.9,0) node[right] {\(x\)};
    \draw[->] (0,-4.7) -- (0,4.9) node[above] {\(y\)};

    \draw[gray!20, step=1] (-4,-4) grid (4,4);

    \foreach \x in {-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3} {
        \foreach \y in {-3,-2,-1,0,1,2,3} {
            \draw[->, blue!65!black, thick]
                (\x,\y) -- ++({-0.20*\y},{0.20*\x});
        }
    }

    \draw[thick] (0,0) circle (4);
    \node at (0,-5.25) {\(\mathbf V(x,y)=\frac14(-y,x)\)};
\end{tikzpicture}

subsection.p:
Recall from  that gradients cross
level curves at right angles. So a gradient field is not just a collection of arrows;
it is tied to the contour map of the scalar field that produced it.
